Load is up in CA and so is the potential for selling load curtailment 
products to customers.


BOTTOMLINES:

████ has asked the ████ to approve participation of E-19 and ███████████████████ customers in the ███ A/S load participation pilot program (filed ████ 
7).

███ has asked the ████ to approve that all customers on its █████████████Interruptible tariff can participate in the ███ A/S load participation pilot 
program (filed ████ 7).

████ approved the ███'s Load Participation pilot progam and pricing on ████ 
████████, calling it an innovative program.

This appears to be a total GREEN LIGHT for █████ to move forward with 
customers.


PROCESS:

The utilities filed advice letters.  Comments are due on ████ 27.  Unless you 
tell us otherwise, we plan to file and seek expedited treatment. (The ████ 
has no required timetable in which to respond.)  We expect the ████ to 
approve them -- there is pressure from many fronts to DO something about load 
participation in the market.  Both have asked for a ███████ effective date.


DETAILS:

███'s is a much better document and makes a good case for ████ approval, even 
though the the customers are already benefitting from providing the utilities 
with the option to curtail during system emergencies. ███ proposes the 
following approach to prevent "double-dipping" by the customers:  If the ███ 
directs ███ to activate its load curtailment program during the time period 
that the customer has an accepted bid from the ███ in the A/S market, ███ -- 
working with the ███ -- will adjust the customer's bill to avoid double 
payments.  ███ provides no more information, but, on principal, this seems 
fair to me.  We'll have to watch to see what the proposed procedure would be.

████ doesn't say much except that it is "unable" to offer this to bundled 
customers (oh, gee -- must be more of those "system constraints") until 
"later" (unspecified).  I would expect large customer groups to argue about 
that -- but it gives us the opportunity to push direct access.  ████ didn't 
have much to offer on the "double-billing" issue -- it said either ████ could 
change the customers bill or the ███ could adjust its payment.

████ threw out all the protests by various parties (e.g., ███, M-S-R, other 
munis) and approved the ███'s proposal.  The big issues were:  supposed 
improper allocation of demand relief program costs (███ allocates it to all 
SCs based on metered demand during all hours of the program);q request to 
charge those who are out of balance for most of the costs; the need to file 
pro forma agreement in advance (████ said ███ doesn't have to); and the 
supposed overly restrictive program participation. If you want to know more 
about the order, give me a call.

